{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491520"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"967"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/967"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.45,0.11,0.17,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"967"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/967"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"967"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91407"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46026"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man is being followed up in a surveillance program for an abdominal aortic aneurysm that was diagnosed as an incidental finding twelve months ago when he had a CT scan for an episode of diverticulitis. The diameter of the aneurysm was 4.8 cm. At today\u0027s appointment the patient denies back or abdominal pain. He has a medical history of hypercholesterolaemia (well-controlled). His medications include atorvastatin. He is a non-smoker. His blood pressure today is 125/73 mmHg. His current physical examination is unremarkable. His recent ultrasound shows the aneurysm is now 5.2 cm in diameter.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound surveillance in three months","Ultrasound surveillance in six months","Ultrasound surveillance in 12 months","Elective endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR)","Repeat CT scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is variation in the international guidelines for the surveillance of asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs), the 2024 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) guidelines are most widely followed, including in Australia and New Zealand. The ESVS guidelines recommend the following monitoring schedule for asymptomatic patients according to AAA diameter:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25 - 29 mm: ultrasound every five years\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E30 - 39 mm: ultrasound every three years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E40 - 49 mm (men) or 40 \u2013 44 mm (women): annual ultrasound\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u226550 mm (men) \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u226545 mm (women): \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound every six months.\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226555 mm (men) or \u226550 mm (women): most surgeons would consider offering surgical repair; note that the threshold for elective repair in women is lower due to higher rupture risk at smaller diameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that these are general guidelines, and different monitoring protocols may be utilised for patients with AAAs based on clinician judgement and patient factors (e.g. life expectancy, suitability for future repair, patient preferences).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this particular case, there has been a 4 mm increase in AAA sac size in twelve months. This is not classified as a rapidly growing aneurysm (\u0026gt;5 mm per six months or \u0026gt; 1cm per year). High risk factors for AAA rupture include female gender, smoking and rapid growth of AAA (\u0026gt;1 cm per year)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndications for\u003Cstrong\u003E elective endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR)\u003C/strong\u003E include an AAA measuring 5.5 cm or larger in males or 5 cm in females, or other high risk features including rapid growth of AAA (\u0026gt;1 cm/year) or a symptomatic AAA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has already had a CT scan which incidentally found the AAA. There is no need for a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat CT\u003C/strong\u003E. It can be measured via ultrasound, a simpler and non-invasive imaging modality. A CT angiogram is performed to interrogate the anatomy of the AAA when it reaches the threshold size of 5.5 cm to plan intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["AAA measuring 5.5 cm or larger typically require surgical management","AAA measuring \u003C 5.5 cm are often monitored with ultrasound surveillance, unless high risk features are present that makes surgical management necessary."],"references":["ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf","Theivendran M, Chuen J. Updates on AAA screening and surveillance. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018;47(5):259-263. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/may/aaa-screening-and-surveillance","Chaikof EL, Dalman RL, Eskandari MK, Jackson BM, Lee WA, Mansour MA, et al. The Society for Vascular Surgery practice guidelines on the care of patients with an abdominal aortic aneurysm. J Vasc Surg. 2018;67(1):2-77.e2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29268916/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91407"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"967"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91407"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:27:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:28:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"967"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109041"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/175"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Abdominal aortic a